let's think about how the
mean changes if you multiply.

00:02:17.670 --> 00:02:19.585
So if you take your data

00:02:19.585 --> 00:02:23.464
and if I were to multiply
it times five, what happens?

00:02:23.464 --> 00:02:26.047
So this equals this times five.

00:02:28.352 --> 00:02:32.566
So now all the data points
are five times more.

00:02:32.566 --> 00:02:35.210
Now what happens to my mean?

00:02:35.210 --> 00:02:38.627
Notice my mean is now five times as much.

00:02:39.607 --> 00:02:41.784
So the measures of central tendency,

00:02:41.784 --> 00:02:43.550
if I add or subtract,

00:02:43.550 --> 00:02:46.832
well I'm gonna add or subtract
the mean by that amount,

00:02:46.832 --> 00:02:48.472
and if I scale it up by five

00:02:48.472 --> 00:02:50.097
or if I scaled it down by five,

00:02:50.097 --> 00:02:53.131
well my mean would scale up
or down by that same amount,

00:02:53.131 --> 00:02:56.170
and if you numerically looked
at how you calculate a mean,

00:02:56.170 --> 00:02:59.641
it would make sense that this
is happening mathematically.

